    <title type="html"><![CDATA[Machine Learning]]></title>
    <link href="http://knmsyk.github.io/blog/2015-05-19-machine-learning.html"/>
    <updated>2015-05-19T00:00:00+09:00</updated>
    <id>http://knmsyk.github.io/blog/machine-learning</id>
    <content type="html"><![CDATA[<div id="outline-container-sec-1" class="outline-2">
<h2 id="sec-1">Link</h2>
<div class="outline-text-2" id="text-1">
<ul class="org-ul">
<li><a href="https://class.coursera.org/ml/lecture/index">https://class.coursera.org/ml/lecture/index</a>
</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
<div id="outline-container-sec-2" class="outline-2">
<h2 id="sec-2">Introduction</h2>
<div class="outline-text-2" id="text-2">
</div><div id="outline-container-sec-2-1" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="sec-2-1">What is machine learning</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-2-1">
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>New capability for computing without explicit programming.
</li>
<li>Mimic of human learning system.
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>Mining, pattern recognition, imitation &#x2026;
</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<p>
<!-- more -->
</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div id="outline-container-sec-3" class="outline-2">
<h2 id="sec-3">Supervised learning</h2>
<div class="outline-text-2" id="text-3">
</div><div id="outline-container-sec-3-1" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="sec-3-1">What is supervised learning</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-3-1">
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>To get a hypothesis, estimator or classifier of test samples (Task) from training samples (Experience).
</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
<div id="outline-container-sec-3-2" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="sec-3-2">Minimizing cost function</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-3-2">
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>Choose coefficients &theta; so that hypothesis \(h (x)\) is close to output \(y\) of experience.
</li>
<li>objective function, cost function (minimization), utility function (maximization) : \(J\)
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>sum of squared root error
$$ J ( \theta ) = \sum_{i=1}^m ( \hxi ) - \yi )^2 $$
</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
<div id="outline-container-sec-3-3" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="sec-3-3">Gradient descent (GD)</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-3-3">
<p>
repeat until convergence {
 $$ \theta_j : = \theta_j - \alpha \pd{ \theta_j }{ J ( \theta ) } $$
}
</p>
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>\(j = 0\)
</li>
</ul>
<p>
$$ \pd{ \theta_0 }{ J ( \theta ) } = \frac 1 m \sumim ( \hxi - \yi ) $$
</p>
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>\(j \neq 0\)
</li>
</ul>
<p>
$$ \pd{ \theta_j }{ J ( \theta ) } = \frac 1 m \sumim ( \hxi - \yi ) \xi_j $$
</p>
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>simultaneous update
</li>
<li>can converge to a local minimum even with <b>the learning rate &alpha; fixed</b>.
</li>
<li>\(J\) should decrease after every iterations.
</li>
</ul>
</div>
<div id="outline-container-sec-3-4" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="sec-3-4">Feature scaling</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-3-4">
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>Make sure features are on a similar scale because non-scale features take long time to converge in GD.
</li>
<li>learning rate should be same scale on any features.
</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div id="outline-container-sec-3-5" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="sec-3-5">Linear regression</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-3-5">
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>Multivariable model
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>\(\hx = \theta_0 + \theta_1 x_1 + ... + \theta_n x_n = \ve \theta^\T \ve x\)
</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
<div id="outline-container-sec-3-6" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="sec-3-6">Normal equation (NE)</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-3-6">
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>MeThod to solve for &theta; analytically
</li>
<li>Set: \(J ( \theta ) = 0\)
</li>
<li>Design matrix: \(X = \left[ \ve x^{(1)^\T}; \ve x^{(2)^\T}; ... ; \ve x^{(m)^\T} \right] \in \R^{m \times n}\)
</li>
<li>\(\theta = ( X^\T X )^{-1} X^\T y\)
</li>
</ul>
</div>
<div id="outline-container-sec-3-7" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="sec-3-7">comparison GD and NE</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-3-7">
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>GD
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>Need to choose &alpha;
</li>
<li>Needs many iteration
</li>
<li>Work well even when #features is large
</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li>NE
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>No need to choose &alpha;
</li>
<li>Don’t need iteration
</li>
<li>Need to compute \(( X^\T X )^{-1}\) : \(O ( n^3) )\)
</li>
<li>Slow if #features is very large
</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
<div id="outline-container-sec-3-8" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="sec-3-8">non-invertivility</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-3-8">
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>Reason. 1
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>Redundant features ( linearly dependent )
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>e.g. \(x_1 =\) size in \(feet^2, x_2 =\) size in \(m^2\)
</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li>Reason.2
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>Too many features
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>e.g. examples &lt;&lt; features
</li>
<li>&#x2013;&gt; Delete some features, or use <b>regularization</b>
</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div id="outline-container-sec-3-9" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="sec-3-9">Classification</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-3-9">
</div><div id="outline-container-sec-3-10" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="sec-3-10">Logistic Regression (LR)</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-3-10">
</div><div id="outline-container-sec-3-10-1" class="outline-4">
<h4 id="sec-3-10-1">hypothesis representation</h4>
<div class="outline-text-4" id="text-3-10-1">
<p>
$$ \hx = g( \theta^\T x ) = \dfrac{ 1 }{ 1 + e^{- \theta^\T x } } $$
</p>
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>\(\hx \in [0, 1]\)
</li>
<li>\(\hx\) : estimated probability that \(y = 1\) on input \(x\)
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>\(\hx = P(y = 1 | x; \theta)\)
</li>
<li>e.g. \(h(\theta) = 0.7\) tell patient that 70% chance of tumor being malignant
</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
<div id="outline-container-sec-3-10-2" class="outline-4">
<h4 id="sec-3-10-2">Decision boundary</h4>
</div>
<div id="outline-container-sec-3-10-3" class="outline-4">
<h4 id="sec-3-10-3">Cost function</h4>
<div class="outline-text-4" id="text-3-10-3">
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>\(\hx\) is modeled by \(P(y = 1 | x; \theta)\). In Linear regression, \(y\) is Real number, on the otherhand, in Logistic regression, \(y\) is \(0\) or \(1\).
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>We should consider a cost function that is suitable for the model.
</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li>\(y = 1\)
</li>
<li>if \(y = 1\)
</li>
</ul>
<p>
$$ \cost( \hx, y ) = - \log ( \hx ) $$
</p>
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>if \(y = 0\)
</li>
</ul>
<p>
$$ \cost( \hx, y ) = - \log ( 1 - \hx ) $$
</p>
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>simplified
</li>
</ul>
<p>
$$ \cost( \hx, y ) = - y \log ( \hx ) - ( 1 - y ) \log ( 1 - \hx ) $$
</p>
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>minimization
</li>
</ul>
<p>
$$ \min \dfrac 1 m \sumim \cost( \hxi, \yi ) $$
$$ \min \dfrac 1 m \sumim \left(- \yi \log ( \hxi ) - ( 1 - \yi ) \log ( 1 - \hxi ) \right)$$
</p>
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>GD
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>Algorithm looks identical to linear regression!
</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<p>
$$ \theta_j := \theta_j - \alpha \dfrac 1 m (\hxi - \yi) \xi_j $$
</p>
</div>
</div>
<div id="outline-container-sec-3-10-4" class="outline-4">
<h4 id="sec-3-10-4">Multiclass classification</h4>
<div class="outline-text-4" id="text-3-10-4">
</div><div id="outline-container-sec-3-10-5" class="outline-4">
<h4 id="sec-3-10-5">one-vs-all</h4>
<div class="outline-text-4" id="text-3-10-5">
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>\(\hcx\) : estimated probability that \(y = c\) on input \(x\)
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>\(\hcx = P(y = c | x; \theta)\)
</li>
<li>On a new test input \(x\), pick the class \(c\) that $$\hat c = \argmax_c \hcx$$
</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div id="outline-container-sec-3-11" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="sec-3-11">Regularization</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-3-11">
</div><div id="outline-container-sec-3-12" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="sec-3-12">What for?</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-3-12">
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>over-fitting / under-fitting: fail to generative to new examples
</li>
<li>Addressing over fitting
<ol class="org-ol">
<li>reduce number of features
<ol class="org-ol">
<li>-&gt; manually select features
</li>
<li>-&gt; model selection algoritm
</li>
</ol>
</li>
<li><b>Reguralization</b>
<ol class="org-ol">
<li>-&gt; reduce magnitude/value of &theta;
</li>
<li>-&gt; even if keep all a lot of features, works well
</li>
</ol>
</li>
</ol>
</li>
<li>make the curve to smooth
</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
<div id="outline-container-sec-3-13" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="sec-3-13">Cost function</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-3-13">
<p>
$$ J(\theta) = \dfrac{1}{2m} \sumim ( \hxi ) - \yi )^2 + \lambda \sumjn \theta_j^2 $$
</p>
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>&lambda; is two large -&gt; under-fitting
</li>
<li>&lambda; is two small -&gt; over-fitting
</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
<div id="outline-container-sec-3-14" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="sec-3-14">GD</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-3-14">
<p>
repeat until convergence {
 $$ \theta_j : = \theta_j - \alpha \pd{ \theta_j }{ J ( \theta ) } $$
}
</p>
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>\(j = 0\)
</li>
</ul>
<p>
$$ \pd{ \theta_0 }{ J ( \theta ) } = \frac 1 m \sumim ( \hxi - \yi ) $$
</p>
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>\(j \neq 0\)
</li>
</ul>
<p>
$$ \pd{ \theta_j }{ J ( \theta ) } = \frac 1 m \sumim ( \hxi - \yi ) \xi_j + \dfrac{\lambda}{m} \theta_j$$
</p>
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>-&gt; \(\theta_j : = \theta_j ( 1 - \alpha \dfrac \lambda m )  - \alpha \frac 1 m \sumim ( \hxi - \yi ) \xi_j\)
</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
<div id="outline-container-sec-3-15" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="sec-3-15">NE</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-3-15">
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>suppose \(m \leq n (X \in \R^{m \times n}: \sharp examples \times \sharp featues)\) and \(\lambda > 0\)
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>- $$\theta = \left( X^\T X + \lambda \fourfourdiag{0}{1}{:}{1} \right)^{-1} X^\T y$$
</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<p>
#- - $$\theta = \left( X^\T X + \lambda \fourfour{0}{}{}{} {}{1}{}{} {}{}{:}{} {}{}{}{1} \right)^{-1} X^\T y$$
#- - $$\theta = \left( X^\T X + \lambda \thrthr{0}{}{} {}{1}{} {}{}{1} \right)^{-1} X^\T y$$
</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
